--- !u!114 &378852114
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 378852111}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "This area displays your display info as readable by the game. \n\nFor
    most games this is likely the information they have. So if anything is incorrect
    here, you may experience issues because of it. \n\nLets go over some of the relevant
    data...\n\nHDR Active:\nDoes the display currently have HDR active?\n\nHDR Avaialble:\nIs
    the display capable of enabling HDR. If this is true but HDR is not active, for
    the purposes of this demo at least I reccomend closing the game and enabling
    HDR in your windows display settings.\n\nMax Full Frame Luminance:\nI'm not sure
    exactly how this information is set, but it seems to either come from calibration
    or the manufactuer. What this number means is what is the max brightness capable
    when the whole screen is filled with a max luminance white. Because of things
    like ABL (Auto Brightnes Limiting) used to avoid overheating and burn-in, the
    peak brightness of a display depends on various factors like how big the area
    and how long it's been displayed.\n\nMax Luminance 10%:\nAgain this number is
    likely determined from calibration software or the display manufactuer. Apparently
    this number is based on a 10% window, it can be useful for an average but do
    not view this number as a hard limit. This number is likely lower than your displays
    actual peak brightness. Some displays are better at lower window sizes some at
    larger varying by 100nits even. This value is likely to avoid clipping.\n\nMin
    Luminance:\nI've never seen this value visible elsewhere on windows, I would
    assume in most cases this value should be zero. Perhaps it exists assuming a
    persons visibility is low. May have accessibility implications...\n\nWindows
    Paper White:\n\"Paper White\" is often the SDR peak brightness in windows, it's
    also often UI brightness. What paper white means in the name is basically, if
    you have a sheet of paper in a well lit room, how bright is it? Generally the
    standard is something like 200 nits. But I've seen anywhere beyween 80-300 nits.
    This value specifies windows, cause it should be determined by the SDR brightness
    value in the HDR settings on windows. As for this game it's paper white value
    is set to 200 for consistency.\n\nAutomatic Tone Mapping:\nThis one I'm iffy
    on until I see more feedback, but i believe, if Unity determines a displays peak
    brightness to be below a certain threshold, it will then tonemap the display
    to see more colors. This is a good feature if thats how it works, but one that
    makes these tests invalid. Your info may read as 1500nits display but thats simply
    the range unity allows you to see. OR if this is not unity, your display automatic
    tonemapping may cause this. \n\nThis information will be updated based on my
    findings. And I will find new ways to get more accurate information for you.\n"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
