    ratio. What you're looking for is \"Blooming\" and what that means is a halo
    around a bright object in a dark space and how that is handled with a moving
    object. You will see a cube appear and move along the outside of your screen,
    watch the area around the cube. There will be two versions one with SDR values
    and one with HDR values. Lastly you'll see many cubes as a test of multiple regions
    at once and blooming between points. Again with SDR values and HDR values. This
    test will loop.\n\nIf your screen has no local dimming you'll see no blooming
    but either the brightness of the cube or black levels will suffer.\n\nMini-led
    displays tend to have local dimming but are usually the best case scenario for
    blooming.\n\nOn an OLED this shouldn't present any blooming since those displays
    don't need local dimming to have deep blacks and bright whites. Though they generally
    don't get as bright as mini-led for now. \n\nDo understand this is a test of
    extreme circumstances. You may see blooming in this test, but never when watching
    a movie or playing a game. IF you're viewing this on a TV, it's  PC or \"Game
    mode\" may also have a weaker local dimming algorithm than other modes designed
    for movies. This is due to reducing input lag. "
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: 2180264, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
