--- !u!114 &909167116
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 909167113}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "<size= 48>Color + Luminance!</size>\nOr at least thats how I like to think
    of it. HDR is color plus the brightness that color needs to be. \n\nThis is also
    a good way to think of how displays work. An SDR display simply see color (0-255
    values, or 0-1 for linear colors with fractions for inbetweens) and then displays
    those colors as bright as it can. \n\nWhile an HDR display has both the hue and
    the luminence of that hue. It can not only display red, but also show how bright
    that red should be. Neon is often the most striking in HDR.\n\n<size= 48>The
    difference between White and Light!</size>\nAnother way to think of HDR, see
    HDR has this concept called \"Paper White\" if you've ever played an HDR game
    you may have seen this option. The idea is the value of \"Paper White\" is the
    value of a well exposed well lit piece of paper. Often this value is around 200nits.
    But HDR displays go much brighter, 600, 1000, 1500 nits and greater! \n\nThat
    \"Paper White\" becomes the difference between a \"flash light pointing at the
    screen\" and a \"white table in day light\" on the screen. This is something
    challening for SDR. Cause in SDR white is white. Anything else is just gray.
    So there's nothing to distinguish these two entirely different objects. If the
    two things are shown at the same time some degree of color may distinguish the
    two, but it's nowhere near as dramatic an HDR display could show. \n\n<size=
    48>And thats not all!</size>\nThis is just a base line introduction, in the future
    I will update this to be a full walkthrough on the basics of HDR, why it's IMO
    the most important display tech since HD, and how to determine good HDR and bad
    HDR. Because HDR is slowly becoming mainstream, and due to the nature of HDR
    there's many layers to how content can be viewed. \n\nThere's the display, content,
    and in some cases the hardware it's played on. If one of these three, but mostly
    the first two have a problem the experience can be severely mitigated. \n\nAs
    such I want to inform people on why one display looks better than another, why
    one game may look better than another game. And also how game developers can
    make sure their content is compelling and why there's a growing demand for HDR
    support in games. And why things like auto HDR while useful in some cases, is
    not a replacement for proper HDR support. \n\nPlease keep an eye out for updates.
    \n\n"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: 2180264, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
