  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "I want to zone in on that Max luminance number cause in some games that
    causes a problem. \n\nSee apparently multiple games will simply use this value
    as the default rather than provide accurate configurable nit values. \n\nThis
    means some games may not be able to be as bright as they could be. \n\nFor me
    personally, I would rather be stuck with a higher value and have some clipping
    than a lower value than my display is capable of. \n\nI understand why this value
    is here, there's variance in measurements and 10% window is the best bet. But
    games should always allow adjustment and be clear on what that adjustment is
    doing.\n\nFor example, a HDR game can have a brightness slider when in HDR this
    can mean several things:\n\n  1. <indent=7%>Either it increases the peak brightness,
    useful for maintaining visual consistency but getting more \"pop\". This is especially
    im portant when some games are modest in their brightness. </indent>\n  2. <indent=7%>Elevates
    the exposure curve, making the game look brighter in a natural way</indent>\n 
    3. <indent=7%>Or the worst case push up black levels resulting in grayish blacks
    and an overall faded image.</indent>\n\nAs a result of this disparity someone
    could play a game be worried about the last scenario and result in a less colorful
    experience than they should have gotten. A 50% brightness slider brings a ton
    of questions. For example Ratchet and Clank seem to be the second case, i played
    most of the game at 50% when 100% actually felt like a better experience. Death
    Stranding is the first case, buit that game as a weird brightness curve so setting
    it to 100% can make white lights look green. The demo version of Lies of P had
    the third case, which made the brightness slider useless. \n\nThe first and second
    cases are the only really acceptable scenarios, and hard locking to what windows
    says is the peak brightness should also be avoided. It's a fine default but not
    good permanent. \n\nEspecially when this number from some manufactuers is not
    reported properly at all. I've had friends buy displays and they simply looked
    all wrong for reasons like this. "
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: 2180264, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
