--- !u!114 &1206890519
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1206890516}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "Here we have multiple color gradients similar to the color test, but this
    time the point is not brightness, but smooth gradients. HDR is not just about
    bright colors, it's also about color range which can solve a lot of problems
    resulting in devs avoiding certain circumstances.\n\nWithout color range you
    get color banding, where instead of seeing a smooth gradient you'll see lines
    in the colors cause it's not possible for the display or the image itself does
    not have the color information.\n\nThe interesting thing about HDR is that it's
    not an end all soluton, you see texture's also may need to be HDR in order to
    be smooth. You may have HDR support in a game, but then zoom in on a texture
    and see color banding. This is not a flaw of HDR but often a result of compression.
    HDR colors use more memory, so often textures are SDR. Exceptions being when
    a texture is emissive, or things like a skybox. \n\nThe above gradients are made
    with high resolution textures and are as uncompressed as possible to give them
    the best chance to avoid banding, this is to show the true limit of the color
    space. Normally both SDR and HDR textures would have some degree of texture compression
    which would signifigantly increase banding. So while you will see some banding
    in the SDR gradients, it would normally be much worse. Consider these gradients
    the absolute best case scenario, and not what you commonly find in games.\n\nColor
    banding is often most visible in darker scenes, we'll demonstrate this in the
    screenshot demo button above.\n\nLets go into a few notes: \n\n   \u2022<indent=5%>The
    degree of color banding on your display can depend on the quality of your display.
    Some displays reduce color banding one way or another. In HDR enabled mode tho
    you may see more color banding than usual cause the display ideally shouldn't
    need to work as hard to reduce banding with HDR color. Lastly if you still see
    a lot of color banding with the HDR gradients this may reflect your display quality
    aswell or be some other issue.</indent>\n\n   \u2022<indent=5%>Auto-HDR does
    not solve color banding issues, infact it may make them worse.</indent>\n\n  
    \u2022<indent=5%>I discovered Unity has a feature to mitigate this problem quite
    thoroughly, in the camera settings there's a \"dithering\" toggle. While this
    doesn't add color depth and thus won't give you detail, you will no longer see
    harsh lines between transitions. This is easily a good enough solution for most
    people. Note tho, Unity NEEDS the HDR color information internally in order to
    do it's dithering. This mean the feature does not help with texture banding,
    it needs to be processing an already HDR image. Hence in the above case only
    the HDR mode would look smoother. This setting also benefits HDR a bit too it
    seems. The feature is off here though to provide a more universal example. But
    I may add a toggle in the future.</indent>\n\n   \u2022<indent=5%>The larger
    your display the worse colorbanding can be, the farther a transition of colors
    needs to travel the more colors needed to make that transition smooth. I don't
    know the exact sizes this is most obvious but for me displays around 50 inches
    suffer easily</indent>\n\n   \u2022<indent=5%>The brighter your display may also
    affect how much color banding you see.</indent>\n"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: 2180264, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
